<TEXT>
mourners bade farewell friday to a nun killed 
in a nicaraguan ambush saying her life was forfeited to violence 
in a world that needs peacemakers 
nearly 300 friends and family members attended a memorial 
service at the home church of sister maureen courtney one of two 
nuns killed monday evening when their pickup truck was attacked by 
assailants in northeastern nicaragua 
some wept as a coffin draped in red roses was borne between two 
rows of women parishioners 
we feel a right to be angry at this senseless death this loss 
of innocent human life archbishop rembert weakland of milwaukee 
told mourners at an evening service in fond du lac about 50 miles 
north of milwaukee 
if we are encouraged by their example to move from here to 
make this world a place of peace and love through the mutual 
service we give to one another then senselessness will be turned 
into fullness of life he said 
about 20 nicaraguans who have worked with the sisters of st 
agnes sang a spanish hymn pescador de hombres and several 
prayers were said in spanish 
sister courtney 45 a milwaukee native and sister teresa 
rosales 24 of nicaragua were members of the fond du lacbased 
sisters of st agnes auxiliary bishop pablo schmitz of bluefields 
nicaragua a native of fond du lac and sister francisca colomer 
24 of nicaragua were wounded in the attack 
sister courtneys body was flown to the united states on 
thursday night an earlier service for her was in milwaukee and a 
private burial was scheduled saturday 
the rev tom wittliff a roman catholic priest and family 
friend told mourners in milwaukee that sister courtney was a 
victim whose sacrifice would become a eucharist for others 
on that road in nicaragua whatever traps were set whatever 
shots were shot the spirit of christ was being continued 
wittliff said the world has enough of the military it has 
enough clowns what the world needs now is people who will give 
sister jean salchert a member of the order prayed give us 
the courage to put our life on the line where there is war and 
violence may we be peacemakers 
two protesters carried signs outside one said stop the 
bloodshed and contra aid another read contra aid murder by 
proxy 
sisters of st agnes in nicaragua said evidence at the scene 
implicates contra rebels in the ambush the usbacked contras are 
fighting the leftist nicaraguan government 
the nicaraguan government has blamed the ambush on the contras 
although a spokesman for the rebels on wednesday denied any 
involvement in the killings 
sister collette hartman a friend of sister courtneys said 
members of the international commission for the protection and 
promotion of human rights were investigating the ambush 
