<TEXT>
a former accountant for the department of housing 
and urban development pleaded guilty friday to one count of theft 
from the us government for allegedly embezzling 1 million from a 
hud rentsubsidy program 
douglas r turner entered the plea before us district court 
judge james carrigan as part of an agreement that called for three 
other theft counts to be dropped in exchange for his guilty plea 
turner 38 could be sentenced to a maximum 10 years in prison 
and fined up to 250000 no sentencing date has been set 
turner was indicted aug 29 for allegedly embezzling 1 million 
from hud and putting the funds to his own use he has been free on 
personal recognizance bond since that time 
turner was a 28000ayear supervisory accountant in huds 
denver regional office 
prosecutors say turner used a government computer to 
electronically transfer about 1 million from the hud section 8 
rentsubsidy program to the bank account of a real estate company 
he owned green view developers inc green view developers was not 
eligible to participate in the program 
the transfers occurred between december 1988 and may 1989 and 
turned up during a routine audit prosecutors said 
investigators said turner apparently found an account number for 
a housing project once used by hud and made charges to that account 
to make it appear the section 8 program funds were being spent 
legitimately 
he allegedly used this system to wire money on at least four 
occasions from the us treasury into the colorado state bank 
account of green view developers 
when the investigators began investigating turners role in the 
affair they allegedly found a burgeoning stock portfolio recently 
purchased real estate and a 500000 custom home under 
construction they said turner also bought a car with the money 
assistant us attorney james allison said fbi and hud 
investigators have so far seized property worth 470000 from 
turner that will be used as restitution in the case 
the justice department has also filed a 1 million civil lawsuit 
against turner in an effort to recover the remainder of the 
embezzled funds 
the civil and criminal actions are a cooperative effort to 
recover the money with the 470000 already seized to be the only 
restitution in the criminal proceeding said turners attorney 
dianna degette 
turners case emerged at the height of concern over allegations 
of widespread fraud in the denver hud operation us attorney mike 
norton said that investigation is still continuing 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

