<TEXT>
mike royko says people in the fox valley 
are cheeseheads but the regions officials believe the 
newspaper columnist has been outfoxed 
the eastcentral wisconsin area is busy trying to lure chicago 
businesses and local officials say a series of insults by royko 
only helps their cause 
greg hunt vice president of economic development for the fox 
cities chamber of commerce said roykos column introduced millions 
of readers to fox valley and let them know we are among the 
safest communities in the nation in its promotional effort the 
region compares itself with chicago one postcard shows a chalk 
outline on a sidewalk depicting a chicago murder victim compared 
with a chalk outline of a hopscotch game in the tranquil fox valley 
towns 
the implication brought a stinging attack from royko in his 
column in wednesdays chicago tribune 
most of the cheeseheads are fine citizens content to chomp on 
a bratwurst burp yank on the underside of a cow and wear long red 
underwear to formal social events the pulitzer prizewinning 
columnist wrote theres nothing wrong with long red underwear 
but up there they wear it as an outer garment 
royko wrote that people in fond du lac a community in the fox 
valley appear so tranquil that their eyes are glazed their jaws 
hang slackly and a few drooled 
fox valley marketing inc a business development group sent a 
series of postcards to about 500 paperrelated buinesses in the 
chicago area about a dozen businesses have made inquiries 
the cards maintained that fox valley has many advantages over 
chicago fastermoving traffic a more productive work force 
cheaper energy safer streets better industrial sites and more 
affordable housing 
royko a sharptongued defender of chicago didnt like the 
postcards but he gingerly confessed it was silly to get angry 
like it or not crime has a role in our history countless 
movies and tv drama have been made about chicagos gangsters 
thats all part of our image and while we might not be happy with 
it when was the last time you saw a hit movie about a wisconsin 
farmer kissing his cow he asked 
