<DOCNO> AP900105-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
manuel antonio noriega was named in 
drugtrafficking indictments unsealed feb 5 1988 
an indictment in miami alleges that after he took control of 
panama in 1983 noriega utilized his official positions to 
provide protection for international criminal narcotics 
traffickers including the medellin cartel 
the cartel is said to be responsible for 80 percent of the 
cocaine reaching the united states 
fifteen other people also face charges in the case and 
proceedings have already begun against four of them 
the indictment charges noriega with 12 counts of conspiracy 
racketeering importing drugs and traveling to further the 
conspiracy specifically it accuses him of 
accepting a 46 million bribe from colombias medellin cartel 
to protect shipments of cocaine launder money supply drug 
laboratories and shield drug traffickers from the law 
allowing smugglers to use panama as a way station for 
usbound cocaine 
using his official positions before and after he took power in 
1983 to provide protection for international narcotics traffickers 
arranging for the shipment of cocaine processing chemicals 
including those seized by panamanian police 
laundering cartel narcotics proceeds in panamanian banks 
allowing cartel leaders to shift operations to panama to 
escape a crackdown in colombia after the assassination of that 
countrys antidrug minister of justice 
traveling to havana so cuban president fidel castro could 
mediate a dispute with the medellin cartel after panamanian troops 
seized a drug laboratory that noriega had been paid to protect 
noriega could receive up to 145 years in prison and more than 
11 million in fines if convicted of all charges 
a grand jury in tampa also indicted noriega on three counts of 
marijuana trafficking the justice department has said that noriega 
would be tried in miami first because the case against him there is 
stronger 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900105-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here is a brief look at some legal issues that could be raised 
by the defense for gen manuel antonio noriega in proceedings on 
drug trafficking charges 
the defense could try to force the government to drop charges 
by seeking court disclosure of classified information pertaining to 
noriegas relationship with the cia 
pretrial publicity nationwide could make it difficult to 
assemble an unbiased jury 
evidence seized during the military invasion of panama could 
be subject to exclusion if the warrantless search violates 
noriegas fourth amendment rights 
the arrest and transportation of noriega could have violated 
us law and provisions of both the panama canal treaty and the 
geneva convention 
the court could lack jurisdiction because noriega could be 
considered a political prisoner brought to the united states 
illegally 
the case could be dismissed if the court finds noriega is 
being selectively prosecuted to force him into concessions on 
control of the panama canal and the governing of panama 
noriega could be immune from prosecution if courts recognized 
his stature as de facto head of state of panama the judge in the 
case has already rejected this argument but it is subject to appeal 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900105-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are some comments made by gen manuel antonio noriega about 
his and panamas relationship to the united states 
