<TEXT>
president bush plans to cut four energy 
conservation programs by 85 percent next year sources say a 
proposal critics say would belie stated administration concerns 
about the environment 
in the fiscal 1991 budget the president unveils jan 29 bush 
will propose spending 30 million on the programs the sources said 
thursday this compares to 200 million the programs are pegged at 
this year 
chief among the victims will be the 161 million weatherization 
program under which the government supplies poor families with 
insulation weather stripping and other energysaving materials 
also slashed will be a program that will distribute 25 million 
this year to save energy in schools and hospitals one that will 
spend 10 million to help states publicize conservation measures 
such as van pooling and another budgeted at 4 million that 
assists states in providing energysaving counseling to businesses 
and individuals 
spokesman roger meyer of the department of energy which 
administers the programs and spokeswoman dede spitznagel of the 
office of management and budget which draws up the budget 
declined to comment 
but lobbyists who support the programs criticized the proposal 
if this is true it would be remarkable that a president whos 
concerned about energy conservation and global warming would ignore 
a program offering serious conservation potential said meg 
power lobbyist for the national community action foundation which 
supports programs for poor people 
the department of energy claims that from the weatherization 
programs start in 1977 through 1988 it paid for the 
weatherproofing of 18 million american homes saving an equivalent 
of 45 million barrels of oil annually 
the department says that between 1978 and 1988 the program that 
helps conserve energy at schools and hospitals disbursed 22413 
grants worth more than 700 million and saving 19 billion in 
energy costs 
jeffrey genzer counsel to the national association of state 
energy officials noted the programs were favorite budgetslashing 
targets of former president reagan when he presented his first 
budget to congress last year bush proposed eliminating federal 
spending on them 
what we hoped for was this president would be turning the tide 
of the last few years and trying to support energy efficiency 
genzer said if these numbers are correct that wouldnt be 
consistent with that view 
bush who has pledged to make environmental concerns a priority 
of his presidency signed a proclamation wednesday designating 
april 22 as the 20th annual earth day 
he said the day should inspire us to save the land we love to 
realize that global problems do have local solutions and to make 
preservation of the planet a personal commitment 
for the 1991 fiscal year which begins oct 1 the grammrudman 
deficit reduction law requires that the president submit a budget 
with a shortfall of no more than 64 billion budget experts 
believe this means bush must find about 40 billion in savings in 
his 12 trillion budget 
the two sources who spoke on condition they not be identified 
said they were not certain how the 30 million would be spent among 
the four programs but one said it was likely the money would be 
distributed in the same proportions by which it is now spent 
sources said previously that bush also will propose cutting from 
14 billion to 105 billion another program that subsidizes the 
home heating bills of about 61 million lowincome american 
households 
