<TEXT>
here are some questions and answers on the 
legal situation surrounding former panamanian dictator manuel 
antonio noriega who surrendered to us authorities and now faces 
trial on drugsmuggling charges 
the answers were distilled from interviews with experts 
including two professors specializing in international law and the 
american legal system and a lawyer in international practice 
q can noriega get a fair trial 
a the courts will say he can whats the alternative are we 
supposed to say that someones notoriety prevents him from ever 
being brought to justice the question is not whether people have 
reached any conclusions or have any impressions in the case but 
whether they can put aside their impressions or opinions to judge 
guilt or innocence 
q president bush has called norega a thug other officials have 
had equally harsh assessments can a jury be found that is not 
affected by these characterizations 
a the emotions will quiet down by the time the case comes to 
trial which may be a year or a year and a half or more people 
will forget the judge in the oliver north trial was able to seat a 
jury that claimed to not have seen heard or read about norths 
televised testimony in congress 
q will the manner of bringing him to this country cause 
problems 
a this is a matter of controversy one expert said whatever 
international law problems are raised once the government has 
custody of someone it doesnt matter how it obtained custody so 
long as he gets due process from now on 
q what are the biggest problems in bringing noriega to trial 
a another expert questioned the legality of noriegas 
apprehension under federal law there will be the issue of whether 
or not noriegas property was reasonably seized and searched under 
international law the problem will be whether the terms of the 1904 
extradition treaty between the united states and panama were 
properly adhered to and whether the panama constitution itself was 
violated other problems under international law go to the issue of 
whether the us armed forces have the right to apprehend a 
fugitive from american justice in another country without the 
express consent of the foreign government without detailed 
information lawyers presume the endara government consented 
q if you were his defense lawyer what would be your tactic 
a you would want to attack the credibility of government 
witnesses as hard as possible based on what we know all or many 
of them appear to be drug dealers or people with long criminal 
records you want to pound away as much as possible on the idea 
that you cant convict anyone on testimony from such shaky and 
shabby people 
q will the military activities that brought about noriegas 
surrender be a continuing factor 
a this is an area that is a mine field where the united states 
is really flirting with serious violations of international law and 
risking being branded an international lawbreaker and exposing 
americans in the future to be targets of kidnappings but he 
volunteered to come out of the vatican embassy and surrender 
himself to drug enforcement administration agents and put himself 
voluntarily into the hands of the american law enforcement and 
criminal justice system 
q what are the biggest issues facing prosecutors 
a the indictment is a year old and reflects events that 
happened a long time ago there may be some problems with evidence 
and with witnesses another possible major roadblock will be 
maneuvering by noriegas lawyers to subpoena documents government 
officials including possibly even the president of the united 
states 
q wont the way evidence was obtained in panama breaking into 
noriegas residence be a problem for prosecutors 
a the us attorney in florida claims he has enough evidence in 
florida to successfully prosecute noriega and does not need the 
documentary evidence seized in panama he presumably would not have 
brought the indictments in the first place unless he had already 
compiled sufficient evidence 
q what happens to noriega if he is acquitted 
a the issue will be raised shall he be extradited to panama or 
deported as an undesirable alien in which case he would have to 
find a country that will take him possibly cuba or nicaragua he 
could also face charges in panama regardless of whether he is 
convicted in the united states 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

