manuel antonio noriegas status as a deposed head of state 
probably wont do him any good in us courts legal specialists 
say 
although international lawyers disagree about whether noriega 
could be prosecuted for his official acts most say he cant claim 
immunity for common crimes such as drugrunning that werent 
part of his official duties 
its going to be hard for noriega to say if it is true that 
i was trafficking drugs i did that pursuant to my 
responsibilities as head of state said bruce zagaris a 
washington lawyer who cochairs the american bar associations 
committee on international criminal law 
noriegas lawyers have suggested that he should be entitled to 
immunity because of his office earlier this week one of his 
former attorneys neal sonnett said noriega is entitled to head 
of state immunity 
but early last year after noriega was indicted us district 
judge william hoeveler ruled that the panamanian leader had no 
grounds for such a claim because the state department had never 
recognized his political legitimacy 
and even if noriega were considered a legitimate head of state 
experts say he probably couldnt claim head of state immunity 
first of all its not clear that there is such a thing 
columbia law school professor lori fisler damrosch said 
although as you might expect several recently deposed heads of 
state did make such an argument 
one was deposed philippine president ferdinand marcos whose 
case may offer the closest parallels to noriegas 
after he sought exile in hawaii marcos claimed that the act 
of state doctrine gave him immunity to both civil lawsuits and 
criminal prosecution in the united states the courts ruled against 
him 
the doctrine the 9th us circuit court of appeals said 
is meant to facilitate the foreign relations of the united 
states not to furnish the equivalent of sovereign immunity to a 
deposed leader 
in other words a deposed ruler might be granted immunity but 
only if the us government considers it advantageous in noriegas 
case as ms damrosch said the views of president bush and the 
executive branch are quite clear 
the marcos case differs somewhat from noriegas because marcos 
was living in the united states when he was indicted and his 
alleged crimes were more closely related to his official duties 
legal experts were hard pressed to recall another case of a 
foreign leader being prosecuted outside his country 
most cited the war crimes trials after world warii in which 
high german officials and japans prime minister hideki tojo were 
tried and convicted but they stressed that such trials were 
extraordinary and provide no precedent for ordinary criminal 
prosecutions 
one scholar alfred rubin a professor of international law at 
the fletcher school of law and diplomacy at tufts university said 
the noriega case reminds him of british prosecutions of malay 
sultans in southeast asia in the 19th century 
in the first such case he said a claimant to a sultans throne 
was charged with piracy in 1840 after he intercepted british 
