<TEXT>
president saddam hussein today proposed a 
threepoint plan for reviving stalled peace negotiations with iran 
including direct meetings and an unconditional release of ailing 
and disabled prisoners 
saddam also praised his countrys advanced arms industry and 
warned israel against attacking iraqi scientific or military 
installations after the recent launch of longrange missiles and a 
rocket reportedly capable of putting a satellite in space 
the iraqi president spoke in a 30minute address aired live by 
radio and television to mark the 69th anniversary of the creation 
of the iraqi army 
we are seeking to open a new door for a dignified peace with 
iran he said 
fighting in the eightyear iraniraq war was halted by a 
ceasefire that went into effect aug 20 1988 us and european 
military analysts have estimated that 1 million people were killed 
and 17 million wounded twothirds of them iranians 
the war grew out of border skirmishes between iran and iraq 
after the late ayatollah ruhollah khomeini took power in iran in 
1979 
but iran and iraq had been in dispute for years over the 
120mile shattalarab waterway the confluence of the tigris and 
euphrates rivers that flows into the persian gulf and forms the 
southern boundary between the two countries 
to revive the peace talks saddam suggested that direct 
meetings between representatives of both leaderships be held 
alternately in tehran and baghdad under the auspices of the 
secretariatgeneral of the united nations 
the direct dialogue will aim at reaching a common 
understanding of the clauses of un security council resolution 
598 and fix a timetable for its implementation provided that 
the talks are completed within a period not exceeding three 
months 
the security council adopted the resolution in july 1987 a year 
later both countries agreed to it and stopped the fighting but 
peace talks launched under un sponsorship after the truce were 
quickly deadlocked 
tehran refused to discuss a settlement before iraq withdraw from 
lands it occupied before the ceasefire and baghdad insisted on 
working out a new border demarcation accord that gives it total 
sovereignty over shattalarab waterway 
under a prewar accord the border between the two countries ran 
down the middle of the waterway which forms iraqs sole outlet to 
the gulf 
iran claims iraq holds 1065 square miles of its territory but 
un experts say the iraqis occupy only 260 square miles 
as a second step toward renewing the peace talks saddam 
proposed an immediate exchange of all wounded and sick prisoners 
of war under the supervision of the international committee of the 
red cross 
that he said would be followed by the release of the 
longestheld pows mainly those captured in the early stages of the 
war which broke out in september 1980 
he also called for registering thousands of prisoners who have 
not been included in lists provided to the red cross 
the red cross has registered 50182 prisoners held by iran and 
19284 in iraqi camps but un officials and diplomats say both 
sides together hold at least 100000 pows 
the red cross mediated an agreement to repatriate the ailing and 
crippled pows immediately after the ceasefire but the accord 
broke down after the release of only 400 prisoners with iran and 
iraq accusing each other of falsifying the number of captives who 
were seeking asylum 
the red cross estimates 1000 ailing or disabled pows are still 
held by both sides 
