noriega walked out of the embassy wednesday night surrendered 
to us forces and was flown to florida to face federal 
drugtrafficking charges 
it was not the first time laboa found himself at the center of a 
panamanian political firestorm 
he sheltered guillermo endara after a coup attempt failed to 
overthrow noriega in october endara led the opposition to noriega 
and now is president 
laboa also mediated between the basque separatist organization 
eta and the spanish government of prime minister felipe gonzalez 
besides noriega and a handful of his henchmen four eta members 
sought refuge at the embassy 
laboa said little publicly as he labored through sticky 
negotiations with us military officials who made their 
headquarters at the st agustin church school across from the 
vatican mission 
the papal nuncio was their exclusive conduit to noriega and when 
the former dictator surrendered wednesday night laboa was given 
most of the credit 
father laboa was the most instrumental person in making this 
happen said maj gen marc cisneros commander of us army 
south 
noriega did not find life comfortable inside the twostory 
compound he slept in a small room with a submachine gun under his 
bed 
just in case noriega got ideas laboa told the troops outside 
they could storm the mission if the former strongman took hostages 
laboa kept noriega in strict isolation forbade the embassy 
staff to talk with him let noriegas faulty television set stay on 
the blink and refused to feed him vegetarian meals noriega does 
not eat meat 
on new years eve the priest served noriega pasta one of 
laboas favorite foods 
born in the northern basque town of san juan guipuzcoa in spain 
laboa became a priest at the age of 26 and a lawyer in italy six 
years later he became pope john paul iis representative in panama 
in 1982 
he was visiting salamanca in spain when the us troops invaded 
and hurried back to panama 
noriega wasnt the only one laboa kept under control 
he also had to deal with hundreds of us soldiers who ringed 
the embassy around the clock 
the soldiers set up an outdoor system with four powerful 
speakers and blasted the building with rock heavy metal rap and 
country music 
laboa was not amused word went out that steps would be 
taken if the racket didnt stop it did 
during the first confusing days of noriegas sanctuary troops 
searched laboas car on at least one occasion and he was detained 
while soldiers rummaged in the car for weapons and nondiplomatic 
personnel noriega they hoped 
from a nearby hotel hundreds of reporters and photographers with 
zoom and special night lenses kept vigil 
at dawn laboa would emerge wearing a sweatshirt bearing with 
the word gago a local supermarket he would bend stretch and 
walk at a fast pace on the embassys palmshrouded patio 
in the afternoon he darted in and out of the black iron embassy 
gates in a long white robe spending hours with us officials 
in the end laboas patience wore thin and he was losing some 
of his popularity 
hours before noriegas surrender 20000 demonstrators marched 
to the embassy demanding the unwanted guest be kicked out 
we respect the catholic church read one sign but excuse 
us we dont respect you monsignor laboa 
vatican embassy officials said laboa told noriega bluntly that 
the buildings diplomatic immunity would be lifted at some point 
gen maxwell thurman commander of the southern command in 
charge of the panama invasion said the united states owed laboa 
special thanks 
he said the priest showed extraordinary competence and 
statesmanlike conduct 
