<TEXT>
light trucks and vans would have the same 
crash protection devices as those required for passenger cars under 
a proposed federal regulation 
the installation of air bags or automatic safety belts in the 
front seat of these vehicles could save as many as 2000 lives a 
year said jerry r curry administrator of the national highway 
traffic safety administration 
the agency said thursday that it would phase in the new 
requirement over three years as it did with the rule on crash 
protection for cars 
under the regulation 20 percent of the vans light trucks 
multipurpose passenger vehicles and small buses manufactured in the 
1994 model year would be required to provide the bags or automatic 
safety belts 
the safety features would be required on 50 percent of the 1995 
model vehicles and on all of those manufactured in 1996 
under the rule vehicles that offer a drivers side air bag 
could have a manual safety belt on the passenger side and still 
comply with the agencys standard through the 1997 model year but 
manufacturers that dont provide a drivers side air bag would have 
to install automatic belts for the driver and on the frontseat 
passenger side 
we are encouraging air bags as the technology of choice 
because air bags in combination with existing lap and shoulder 
belts offer the best protection available curry said 
all new passenger cars sold in the united states now must have 
air bags or automatic belts 
they are saving thousands of lives and preventing tens of 
thousands of serious injuries each year curry said the same 
protection should be given to those who choose to buy todays 
popular minivans and light trucks 
deaths and injuries to light truck riders increased from 6500 
in 1984 to 8300 in 1988 he said number of the vehicles sold also 
have increased 
the agencys move drew praise from sen jack danforth rmo 
ranking republican on the senate commerce committee and a longtime 
air bag proponent 
air bag technology has been around since the early 1960s but 
only this year did we see large numbers of cars with air bags 
danforth said we should not go through another long struggle to 
get air bags into the vehicles now used frequently by families 
the rule would apply to all vans trucks buses and multipurpose 
vehicles with a gross vehicle weight rating of 8500 pounds and an 
unloaded vehicle weight of 5500 pounds or less 
included would be motor homes convertibles openbodytype 
vehicles walkin vantype trucks and vehicles carrying 
chassismounted campers 
also under the rule light trucks and passenger cars with only 
two seating positions would have to be equipped to support a child 
safety seat on the passenger side 
the announcement opens a 60day period for public comment on the 
proposed rule afterward the agency will write a final version and 
set a date for implementing it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

