<TEXT>
tradition won over womens rights today as japans 
chief government spokeswoman abandoned her challenge to an ancient 
taboo that bans women from entering the sumo ring 
the battle began in december when chief cabinet secretary 
mayumi moriyama informed the japan sumo association that she 
intended to present the prime ministers cup to the winner of the 
new year grand sumo tournament from inside the ring 
the prime ministers cup since 1978 has been presented by the 
deputy chief cabinet secretary to the winner of the annual 15day 
new years tournament which begins sunday 
but mrs moriyama who last year became the first woman to hold 
the important cabinet post asked to present the award herself to 
challenge a tradition that forbids women from entering the ring a 
raised mound of clay about 14 feet in diameter 
what mrs moriyama meant to do was to raise the issue to 
improve womens social position the deputy cabinet secretary 
nobuo ishihara told reporters friday but after sumo officials 
stated their opposition she decided not to push the issue further 
ishihara said 
futagoyama the chairman of the sumo association told reporters 
today that i dont know how things will change in the future but 
i appreciate her understanding on thursday the former 
wrestler had said the ring is sacred and we must preserve our 
traditions 
it was not until 1778 that women were allowed to watch bouts 
but only on the final day of tournaments 
a century later women were allowed to watch throughout 
tournaments but not permitted to go up on the ring a tradition 
which remains the same to this day even though the 2000yearold 
sport has gained many female fans 
at ryogoku national gymnasium in tokyo which opened in 1909 
women were banned from the first five rows around the ring until 
after world war ii said lora sharnoff in her recently published 
book grand sumo 
although her challenge didnt work this time things have 
changed and i believe they will also change in the future said 
ryoichi maki a secretary to mrs moriyama 
sumo symbolizes the maledominated structure of our society 
said yoko morosawa a researcher on womens issues im glad mrs 
moriyama did this although she wont be able to climb into the 
ring her action definitely contributed to making more people 
realize the problem 
