<DOCNO> AP900105-0086 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
people who play contact sports can be held 
liable for the injuries they inflict on others if their conduct is 
willful or recklessly disregards others safety the state supreme 
court said today 
the high court used a case stemming from a pickup basketball 
game in omaha to spell out when people who participate in contact 
sports can be held responsible for injuries they cause to others 
the judges also provided a definition of reckless behavior 
the case involved a suit brought by joseph dotzler against bruce 
tuttle dotzler suffered two fractured wrists in 1984 when tuttle 
allegedly pushed him during a basketball game at an omaha ymca 
a jury decided the case in favor of tuttle 
the supreme court reversed that decision and ordered a new 
trial saying district judge theordore l carlson didnt properly 
instruct the jury 
the trial court shouldnt have allowed the issue of contributory 
negligence whether dotzlers conduct was partly responsible for 
his own injuries to be considered the supreme court said 
dotzler testified that he was standing still when he was 
allegedly pushed by tuttle tuttle said he wasnt particularly 
aware of dotzlers position on the basketball court 
that was all of the evidence in the record and it was not 
sufficient to permit a finding by the jury of absence of lookout or 
lack of control on dotzlers part chief justice william hastings 
wrote 
jury instructions should be confined to the issues found in 
the pleadings and which find support in the evidence the opinion 
said 
judge c thomas white did not participate in the 60 decision 
the judges said the case raised the issue of what constitutes 
recklessness under nebraska law and what standard of liability 
applies to someone who injures another during a contact sport 
the judges held that a participant in a game involving a 
contact sport such as basketball is liable for injuries only if 
his or her conduct is such that it is either willful or with a 
reckless disregard for the safety of the other player but is not 
liable for ordinary negligence 
the high court defined recklessness in part as the disregard 
for or indifference to the safety of another or for the 
consequences of ones act 
recklessness differs from intentional wrongdoing in that while 
the act must be intended by the actor in order to be considered 
reckless the actor does not intend to cause the harm which results 
from the act the court wrote 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

