<TEXT>
two distant cousins of the aids virus that 
usually are carried by drug users are also fairly common among 
female prostitutes say researchers who interviewed and tested more 
than 1300 prostitutes 
the study released thursday done by researchers at the federal 
centers for disease control in atlanta expands the groups 
considered at risk for the viruses and further underscores the 
importance of publichealth efforts to prevent their spread said 
irvin chen an outside expert who also has done research on the 
viruses 
the viruses called htlvi and htlvii are transmitted much 
like the aids virus through shared hypodermic needles sexual 
intercourse and from infected mothers to their babies 
htlvi has been linked to a type of leukemia and a serious 
neurological disorder as many as 5 percent of those who test 
positive for the virus eventually contract leukemia the cdc 
researchers said 
the second virus htlvii has not been clearly associated with 
disease it is however so closely related to htlvi that tests 
sophisticated enough to differentiate between the two are not yet 
available the researchers said 
for that reason researchers used a test for both viruses on the 
1305 prostitutes examined between 1986 and 1988 the women all 
were older than 18 and had had a median of 2900 sexual encounters 
of those tested 67 percent were found positive for the 
viruses said dr rima khabbaz lead researcher of the study 
reported in fridays journal of the american medical association 
while the single most important risk factor for carrying the 
virus was drug abuse 24 percent of the women who reported no 
history of intravenous drug abuse and had no needle marks also 
tested positive according to the study 
its clear that both of these viruses are found in intravenous 
drug abusers in this country said chen a researcher at the 
university of californialos angeles who specializes in the viruses 
its interesting that theyre finding it in another group 
among female prostitutes it just extends the range of the 
viruses 
the researchers studied women in atlanta miami los angeles 
san francisco southern nevada colorado springs colo newark 
nj and four other new jersey cities 
prostitutes in newark were most likely to carry the viruses 
with 254 percent testing positive while none of the prostitutes 
tested in southern nevada was found to carry the viruses 
khabbaz and chen agreed that the findings carry important 
publichealth implications 
its clear now that all of these viruses are transmitted 
in the same way chen said in the publichealth point of view 
anything that can be done to prevent the spread of these viruses is 
essential 
control measures such as the use of condoms to prevent other 
sexually transmitted diseases should be encouraged khabbaz 
and her colleagues wrote 
finally control measures aimed at intravenous drug use and 
the sharing of needles and other bloodcontaminated injection 
paraphernalia are urgently needed 
