<TEXT>
bush administration policymakers faced with a 
foreign aid squeeze because of the need to reward emerging 
democracies in panama and eastern europe are looking primarily to 
the pentagon budget for possible relief say congressional and 
private sources 
one growing school of thought argues that changes in the worlds 
security balance now mean that us interests abroad are better 
maintained by diplomacy than by threat of force and that at least 
a small amount of the military money saved through arms treaties 
and lessened tensions should go for foreign aid 
others in the administration and on capitol hill are talking 
about nicking the largest current aid recipients countries such 
as israel egypt pakistan turkey and greece to pay for 
assistance to the new democracies that option however is seen as 
more politically difficult and therefore less likely than others 
the administration this week sent a delegation to panama to 
evaluate the need for us assistance in reviving a oncerobust 
economy crippled by american trade sanctions early estimates of 
needed aid are running upwards of 1 billion over several years 
bush also has pledged that eastern european countries that adopt 
democracy and reform their economies can expect help of the sort 
that congress voted last year for poland and hungary which 
together are getting 840 million over the next three years 
but the new aid will have to be found in a foreign assistance 
budget that already is strained beyond its limits leaving some 
friendly countries to do without about a dozen nations that 
normally could expect some us economic aid this year will end up 
with nothing said mark edelman acting administrator of the state 
departments agency for international development 
we have a hell of a problem and its getting tighter and 
tighter and tighter edelman said in an interview 
of the 146 billion in this years foreign aid package israel 
has received 3 billion and egypt 21 billion those two along 
with pakistan greece and turkey get the lions share of us 
economic and military aid and are protected by congressional 
earmarks whats left is parceled out in far smaller amounts to 
several dozen other countries 
as the year wears on and congress begins deliberations on a 1991 
aid bill matters are bound to get worse officials say foreign 
aid is among the least popular programs on capitol hill meaning 
the growing us commitments must somehow be shoehorned into a 
budget that will remain essentially unchanged 
we only have so much said sen bob dole rkan it may 
not be possible for some countries to do quite as well as they 
have in the past the american people understand that we are 
going to have to help in countries like romania and 
czechoslovakia 
theres a bottom line if you want to do more here youve got 
to do less there said edelman 
there is going to be a squeeze predicted william hellert 
an analyst with the overseas development council a 
washingtonbased advocacy group for development in poorer countries 
he noted that not only are panama and eastern europe likely to 
expect new aid from the united states but other countries may make 
claims as well namibia which is gaining its independence from 
south africa and mozambique and angola where settlements of civil 
wars are hoped for 
in addition the united states is faced with taking care of late 
payments to the un peacekeeping force money that comes out of 
the foreign aid bill and with new payments to the international 
development association an arm of the world bank additional money 
will be needed to cope with increased flows of refugees around the 
world 
as new and more politically popular recipients line up at the 
aid window some of the worlds most needy countries fear they will 
get pushed even further back in the queue noted rep lee hamilton 
dind a senior foreign affairs committee member weve been 
squeezing africa for about as long as you can squeeze it 
throughout latin america the growing scarcity of us aid is a 
top concern they have just gone through a lost decade as far as 
development is concerned said hellert are they going to go 
through another one 
