<TEXT>
orders to us factories for manufactured 
goods reached their second highest level in november the 
government said friday in a report that analysts saw as further 
evidence the longest peacetime economic expansion is continuing 
this confirms our expectations that the economy wont drop 
into a recession said thomas runiewicz an economist with the 
wefa group a bala cynwyd pa forecasting organization were 
going to see a slowdown but no recession 
it pretty much conclusively demonstrates that were not 
heading into a recession agreed gordon richards economic policy 
director for the national association of manufacturers 
the commerce department said orders for both durable and 
nondurable manufactured goods jumped 24 percent to a seasonally 
adjusted 2397 billion after edging down 01 percent in october 
they had gained 1 percent in september 
it was the highest level of orders since a record 2399 billion 
was posted in april and the fastest rate of increase since a 28 
percent advance in august 
the report was a bright spot in what has become a mixed picture 
of the manufacturing economy 
the labor department reported friday that the manufacturing 
sector lost another 25000 jobs in december raising to 195000 the 
number of factory jobs lost since march 
however orders for durable goods where much of the 
manufacturing weakness has been concentrated posted a 48 percent 
increase to 1302 billion after a slip of 08 percent in 
october increases were widespread within all the major categories 
runiewicz said that portends good news because factory orders 
are a leading indicator and thus suggest future economic growth 
transportation orders jumped 106 percent to 367 billion 
after a 19 percent gain in october while aircraft orders totaled 
26 billion or 62 percent of the advance the slumping auto 
industry posted a 15 billion gain 
excluding the transportation category orders would have risen 
11 percent 
other major durable goods categories recording gains included 
electrical machinery up 77 percent most of it in defense 
communication equipment nonelectrical machinery including 
computers and a wide variety of industrial equipment up 57 
percent and primary metals up 22 percent 
on the other hand orders for nondurable goods that had been 
the mainstay of the economy in recent months dropped 03 percent 
to 1095 billion after rising 06 percent in october 
richards described the turnaround as a statistical correction 
its pretty typical of economic statistics that when you see 
deviations in one direction chances are its going to be a 
fallback in the other direction at some point he said 
defense orders rose 169 percent to 112 billion after 
falling 10 percent in october excluding defense orders would have 
risen 18 percent 
analysts agreed that nondefense capital goods orders were 
another positive in the november report because they are a 
barometer of business investment plans they were up 77 percent 
after a 18 percent gain in october 
</TEXT>
