candidates for general elections in may 
include a popular prodemocracy leader now under house arrest and a 
phalanx of veterans from the party that wielded authoritarian power 
for 26 years 
according to incomplete reports received friday from the 
election commission 2066 candidates from 96 political parties and 
70 independents will vie for 492 parliamentary seats 
although burmas military rulers ordered house arrest for aung 
san suu kyi the charismatic prodemocracy leader has been allowed 
to file a nomination to run in a constituency in rangoon the 
capital 
ms suu kyi the daughter of independence hero aung san rose to 
prominence in the fall of 1988 as millions of burmese rose up 
against a militaryled government that suppressed political 
freedoms and ruined the countrys economy during its 26year rule 
the uprising was crushed violently by the military and a 
military council has ruled with martial law since then but it 
promised elections in may 1990 no date has been set 
many western diplomats in rangoon and bangkok doubt the polling 
will be fair and free noting widespread arrests of political 
opponents and human rights abuses in the past year 
the only party capable of fielding candidates in all 492 
constituencies is the national unity party which under another 
name was the sole political party in the country from 1962 until 
1988 
the party will field virtually all the prominent leaders of the 
former ruling party the burma socialist program party 
perhaps the most popular of the six national parties is ms suu 
kyis national league for democracy it built up a rapid base of 
support but has been weakened by the arrests of toplevel members 
including party chairman tin oo he was sentenced to three years in 
prison last month for allegedly inciting arrest and attempting to 
divide the army 
similar accusations were made against ms suu kyi but the 
military rulers have not taken legal action against her although 
she remains under house arrest in rangoon 
others who filed nominations are popular leader aung gyi of the 
union nationals democracy party and chit maung chairman of the 
largest leftist party the democratic front for national 
reconstruction 
burmas last multiparty elections were in 1960 the elected 
