the increased demand was widespread across most industries led 
by another big jump in orders for aircraft economists said the 
rise in orders if it continues in coming months should halt the 
slide in manufacturing employment probably by the middle of next 
year 
analysts were still concerned that the slowdown in the overall 
economy which many feared would last until the spring would 
translate into higher jobless rates in the months ahead 
there definitely is some weakness out there in the land 
the steady growth of the service industry is whats keeping us from 
slipping into a recession said economist cynthia latta of 
drimcgraw hill 
during all of last year the unemployment rate fluctuated in a 
narrow range within a tenth of a percentage point of 53 percent 
except for march when it dipped to a 15year low of 5 percent the 
average for the year was 53 percent 
based on a workplace survey manufacturing industries lost 
another 25000 jobs in december bringing factory job losses since 
march to 195000 us manufacturing suffered in 1989 with 
widespread layoffs in auto plants and other factories producing 
bigticket consumer goods 
this job loss has not been enough to pull the country into a 
recession because of a continued boom in the service sector where 
most americans are employed 
in december the service sector added 206000 jobs bringing 
total job growth for the year to 24 million 
theres a kind of tug of war going on to see whether service 
industry increases will pull ahead of the manufacturing losses 
said pierre ellis an economist at the boston co 
the addition of 142000 nonfarm jobs in december was not 
considered a particularly strong advance given that it was 
artificially inflated with the return of about 55000 striking 
telephone workers in new york 
some analysts were concerned by a 06 percent rise in average 
hourly earnings in december which would translate into wage gains 
above 7 percent if it persisted for a year 
however other analysts dismissed the jump as a onemonth 
aberration and not a signal that wage pressures were threatening to 
set off an inflationary spiral they noted that the 41 percent 
increase in hourly wages over the past year was still under 
consumer price inflation which has been increasing by 45 percent 
the labor department on friday revised the november unemployment 
rate to 53 percent which it had earlier reported as 54 percent 
according to a household survey by the department the economy 
produced 17 million new jobs during 1989 bringing the civilian 
work force to 1179 million that was down from job gains of 23 
million in 1988 
construction jobs fell by 38000 in december with analysts 
attributing the drop to the deep freeze that gripped most of the 
nation last month 
transportation employers added 73000 jobs on a seasonally 
adjusted basis last month business services added 14000 health 
services 47000 government 34000 and finance insurance and 
real estate 13000 retail employment grew by 12000 fewer jobs 
than the normally expected seasonal gain 
in a separate calculation of unemployment that counts members of 
the armed services stationed in the united states the december 
jobless rate was unchanged at 53 percent the same as the civilian 
rate 
