the justice department said friday that it 
spent 224000 on a futile attempt to identify the source of an 
unauthorized disclosure of a preliminary criminal investigation 
involving rep william h gray iii 
the department conducted a fivemonth investigation to determine 
who leaked information that the fbi was investigating alleged 
financial irregularities in grays congressional office 
an initial cbstv story that gray was the subject of the 
preliminary investigation prompted a storm of accusations from 
democrats on capitol hill that the republicanrun justice 
department was trying to smear the pennsylvania democrat with news 
leaks 
the department quickly took the unusual step of issuing a 
statement that gray was not a target and was cooperating with fbi 
agents 
the cbs story was particularly embarrassing for attorney general 
dick thornburgh because it was aired as gray was seeking election 
as house majority whip a job he later won thornburgh ordered an 
investigation of the unauthorized leak 
the 224000 included the salaries and travel expenses of 11 fbi 
agents as well as prosecutors and support personnel runkel said 
agents took sworn statements from 109 justice department and fbi 
employees and 10 were asked to take polygraph tests the department 
said 
the investigation was conducted with money already available for 
that purpose runkel said 
during the investigation the justice department told congress 
that it had changed its longstanding policy barring prosecution of 
government officials for unauthorized disclosure of sensitive 
information 
under the new policy officials could be prosecuted for 
conversion or theft of government property by making an 
unauthorized disclosure of information about a criminal 
investigation the charge carries a maximum 10year sentence 
but thornburgh said last week in a letter to congress that there 
would be no prosecutions or disciplinary action because the 
investigation of the gray leak was unable to identify with 
certainty the original source of the disclosure 
