baptists probably the most oppressed 
worshipers under nicolae ceausescu are professing their faith 
openly for the first time since the dictators relentless 
persecution stifled them decades ago 
numerous people from all walks of life including many army 
officers and soldiers have been coming here in the past few days 
to tell us how afraid they had been in the past to say they were 
believers the rev ilie tundrea of bucharests bethany baptist 
church said friday 
as in other countries with rigid communist regimes believers 
were considered unreliable citizens not allowed to hold leading 
positions in an officially atheist system 
no religion was encouraged but tundrea said in an interview 
it was worse for protestants because the authorities could not 
tolerate our evangelical activity 
ceausescu was overthrown dec 22 and the first large baptist 
gathering was held dec 31 in oradea northwestern romania about 
10000 worshipers packed a sports arena with the approval of the 
new authorities 
for the first time since the communist takeover in 1947 state 
radio and tv broadcast a live christmas service from the patriarhie 
cathedral in bucharest 
in recent annual us state department reports on human rights 
the ceausescu regime ranked among the worst offenders it was 
accused of running a police state with no freedom of expression 
and religious tolerance only for such recognized faiths as the 
romanian orthodox or jews 
baptist pastors were denied permission to preach and arrested 
for distributing bibles the communists never recognized the roman 
catholic church because the catholic bishops refused to recognize 
the supremacy of the state 
about 80 percent of romanias 23 million people are believed to 
be nominal followers of the orthodox faith and 6 percent are roman 
catholics 
romania has about 300000 baptists up from 60000 two decades 
ago most of the baptists pentecostals seventhday adventists and 
other protestants are in the western transylvania region and in 
bucharest 
under ceausescu who ruled romania for 24 years the baptist 
church was given special attention because its rapid growth was 
seen as a threat 
the romanian orthodox church was treated more leniently because 
it generally limited itself to such traditional ceremonies as mass 
marriages and funerals 
securitate officers were present at every single service to 
record what was being preached and we were forbidden from 
baptizing tundrea said referring to the ceausescus secret 
police 
he said police cars always were parked outside the church and 
the telephones of leading baptists were tapped 
believers who refused to become informers were harassed at work 
and many were jailed for years after they were accused of being 
servants of western capitalism the pastor said 
official reaction to construction of a church in comanesti 135 
miles north of bucharest illustrated the hardships baptists faced 
under ceausescu 
the building was torn down in 1989 after authorities accused 
local church leaders of stealing construction materials and other 
socialist property and four were imprisoned they were released 
after the revolution 
lack of bibles and other christian books forbidden in romania 
was partially overcome through the efforts of missionaries from 
western europe and the united states who imported the books in 
special hidden compartments in their vans tundrea said 
pastors often were summoned for interrogation by the security 
police and were even forbidden to preach from specific sections of 
the bible 
they could not mention the book of revelations because it 
speaks of the second coming of christ this ceausescu did not 
accept tundrea said while helping unload a dutch truck bringing 
food aid for distribution by his church 
in 1977 a group of pastors wrote a letter to ceausescu 
complaining about persecution in the country tundrea said 
after that every one of us was interrogated each day for six 
weeks he said in a whisper then laughed and said aloud you 
see i am still living in the era before the revolution 
for us the revolution was a miracle we can now be free to 
participate in a christian revival in romania the pastor 
said 
i believe we will have opportunity to print bibles and 
magazines establish new contacts and organize evangelical 
activities because people feel such a big hunger for them now 
