<TEXT>
a judge is not required to warn a 
defendant that he could be making a mistake by serving as his own 
lawyer maines highest court has ruled 
the ruling by the maine supreme judicial court came in the 
appeal of a former policeman with a strongly held dislike for 
attorneys who was convicted of having sex with a child 
former state trooper richard morrison was charged with having 
sex with a 13yearold baby sitter in 1985 he defended himself at 
trial lost the case then hired a lawyer and appealed his 
conviction on grounds that he had inadequate legal representation 
johnson was in jail after surrendering following thursdays 42 
ruling he was sentenced to 10 years 
a popular saying among lawyers is that a person who acts as his 
own attorney has a fool for a client the gist of morrisons 
appeal was that the judge should have warned him how foolish he was 
his lawyer peter b bickerman said he would meet with morrison 
before determining whether to appeal the maine ruling to the us 
supreme court 
its generally believed that the judge should give some kind 
of warning to defendants who act as their own lawyer bickerman 
said but bickerman said guidelines for such warnings have never 
been firmly laid out 
the court majority said morrison had no right to a new trial 
because before his trial he had been warned by family friends 
and even the prosecutor that he should get an attorney morrisons 
wife contacted a lawyer only to have morrison become angry with 
her and refuse the lawyers help said the majority opinion 
written by chief justice vincent l mckusick 
morrison had a strongly held dislike for attorneys and 
despite repeated warnings he never budged from his early decision 
to conduct his own defense at trial mckusick wrote 
the justices said they were refusing to create a rule that would 
throw out convictions of people who represent themselves if the 
trial court failed to give the defendant mirandalike warnings of 
the risks of selfrepresentation and the benefits of counsel on the 
record 
miranda is the landmark us supreme court ruling that requires 
police to read suspects their rights 
the two dissenting justices said morrison should have received 
more than warnings from his wife and fellow troopers 
they noted that the trial judge informed morrison of his 
constitutional right to a lawyer and determined morrison was able 
to afford a lawyer but he did not warn morrison about the dangers 
of selfrepresentation 
the dissenting opinion also quoted from a california case in 
which the us supreme court held that defendants who represent 
themselves should be made aware of the dangers and disadvantages 
of selfrepresentation so that the record will establish that he 
knows what he is doing and his choice is made with his eyes open 
morrison was convicted of rape gross sexual misconduct 
unlawful sexual contact and assault thursdays ruling dismissed 
the conviction on the unlawful sexual contact count saying the 
prosecution had inadequate evidence on that charge that did not 
change morrisons 10year prison sentence bickerman said 
</TEXT>
