east germany on friday lifted a ban on 
singing in public of the original version of its national hymn 
germany united fatherland declaring the anthem written in 1949 
to be part of its cultural heritage 
government spokesman wolfgang meyer said the hymn would once 
again be sung on official radio and television broadcasts 
the hymn was banned by the communist government 20 years ago 
because it implied support for reunification of germany a theme 
long resisted by the east german government 
meyer dismissed concerns that restoration of the hymn could be 
seen as encouragement of rightist elements or support for a formal 
union with west germany 
he said officials decided the song should again be sung because 
it was a part of east germanys cultural identity 
singing the song again means dealing with our own history and 
acknowledgement of the time of those historical conditions and 
thoughts that inspired the hymn meyer said 
germany united fatherland was written by east germanys 
first culture minister johannes r becher 
east germany dropped the national hymn from public gatherings in 
1969 because of its inferences to reunifying east and west germany 
resurrected and facing the future out of ruins let us serve 
you well germany united fatherland the hymn runs in part old 
wants compel us and united we compel it because we must succeed 
so that the sun shines more beautiful than ever before over 
germany 
