<TEXT>
states rights and the intent of congress in 
outlawing age discrimination were the focus of oral arguments 
friday in vermonts appeal of a ruling that bars the state from 
forcing a 71yearold judge to retire 
vermont supreme court justice louis peck is challenging a 
provision in his states constitution that requires judges to 
retire at age 70 
william gray the attorney for the state urged three judges of 
the us 2nd circuit court of appeals to overturn a lower court 
ruling that struck down the mandatory retirement rule 
gray said the ruling upset the balance of power between state 
and federal governments by taking away vermonts right to make 
decisions about its judiciary 
the states of massachusetts connecticut and new mexico have 
filed briefs backing vermont massachusetts and connecticut have 
mandatory retirement provisions for judges new mexico does not 
but filed the brief through the lincoln legal foundation on the 
issue of states rights 
peck who continues to sit on vermonts highest court filed an 
age discrimination complaint with the federal equal employment 
opportunity commission in may five months after he turned 70 his 
retirement had been scheduled to go into effect june 30 
the eeoc picked up pecks case and filed a complaint in federal 
court in vermont where us district judge lee gagliardi ruled 
that peck and other appointed state judges in vermont could not be 
forced to retire because of their age 
gagliardi said state judges were protected by the federal age 
discrimination and employment act which prohibits age 
discrimination against most employees 
gray argued that that act could not be applied in this case 
because it did not specifically name state judges he said there 
had to be a clear congressional intent to preempt a state 
constitution 
that argument found favor with the 1st us circuit court of 
appeals in boston in an earlier ruling on massachusetts mandatory 
retirement provision the 1st circuit ruled it could not find a 
sufficiently clear statement by congress that it intended to 
overrule the clear intent of the people of a state in an area 
intimately and fundamentally related to that states 
selfgovernance 
the 1st circuit ruling has meant judges in massachusetts must 
retire at age 70 
eeoc attorney paul bogas cited a similar case in wyoming in 
which the supreme court found that the states interests were not 
seriously threatened by the federal age discrimination law 
bogas spent most of his arguments countering another position 
forwarded by gray that state judges were covered by an exemption 
to the age discrimination and employment act for elected officials 
and policymaking appointees who work for elected officials 
the constitutional and legal duties of state judges are 
completely independent from the governor who appoints them bogas 
said he said judges clearly were not policy makers 
the appeals court will issue a written ruling at a later date 
peck was not in court for the arguments but two other judges who 
are fighting similar battles were present they were robert satter 
a senior superior court judge from connecticut and justice isaac 
rubin of the appellate division of new yorks supreme court 
</TEXT>
