and the area was secured by deputies as a federal air safety 
inspector made his way to the site 
they have been instructed not to do anything with the engine 
until he gets there said ted lopatkiewicz spokesman for the 
national transportation safety board in washington dc 
the inspection would probably begin saturday lopatkiewicz said 
the engine was found on the ranch of a man who reported hearing 
a loud noise thursday said sheriffs dispatcher fred register 
deputies were unable to check the tip until late friday morning 
because of heavy fog 
the engine fell thursday from the right tailwing of a 
14yearold boeing 727 on a flight from miami to minneapolis with 
139 passengers and a crew of six on board the plane diverted to 
tampa and landed safely 
radar showed the engine separating from the plane and 
investigators believed its sixmile plunge landed it near madison 
officials believe the engine will provide the best evidence on the 
cause of the separation 
boeing spokesman tom cole in seattle noted the 727s three 
engines are each designed to break off if sudden vibrations 
threaten to tear a plane apart and the plane can continue with two 
engines or even with one 
the incident caused little disturbance to passengers and the 
aircraft lost only 100 feet of altitude immediately following the 
engine loss before the incident engines had broken off boeing 
jets three times since 1985 
in each case the pilots landed the planes safely and without 
injuries to passengers but after the last two incidents the 
federal aviation administration ordered emergency inspections of 
the bolts holding the engines in place 
