<TEXT>
president carlos salinas de gortari completed 
an overhaul of his cabinet friday aimed at further developing 
tourism and boosting agricultural production two of mexicos 
principal moneyearners 
a surprise announcement thursday evening said agriculture 
secretary jorge de la vega dominguez was named a special adviser to 
salinas and tourism secretary carlos hank gonzalez 63 would take 
over agriculture 
former gov pedro joaquin coldwell 40 of quintana roo state in 
the yucatan was named tourism secretary on friday 
hanks appointment was hailed by business leaders who have been 
fretting that rising food prices and lagging production from 
mexicos antiquated farms and ranches was fueling inflation and 
eroding export income 
president eduardo garcia suarez of the national chamber of 
commerce urged hank to lift existing prices controls and pave the 
way to attract new investments in agriculture so as to raise 
productivity 
one major problem which every government has ducked in the 60 
years the institutional revolutionary party has been in power is 
the socalled ejido system under which entire villages own 
land that the villagers work in small parcels but by law cannot be 
sold or merged 
the system was revived by the 191020 revolution which called 
for land for everyone who works it land expropriations and 
agrarian reform continued until the early 1980s but now the 
government says there is no more land to expropriate 
mexico once a net exporter of agricultural products has been 
increasingly relying on purchases of wheat corn and other 
foodstuffs abroad to feed its growing population and make up for 
shortfalls in domestic production 
it now spends close to 3 billion a year on these imports 
salinas pledged to modernize mexico from top to bottom when he 
was inaugurated dec 1 1988 for a sixyear term 
word has circulated around government halls that the agrarian 
reform and the agriculture departments will soon be merged under 
hank 
in his one year as tourism secretary hank lined up japanese 
western european and canadian investors helped privatize and 
deregulate the airline industry and laid out plans to build new 
hotels and resorts in a program to double the number of tourists 
coming to mexico by 1994 
about 6 million foreign tourists now visiting mexico annually 
spend an estimated 3 billion a year 
coldwell a businessman and former congressman moved up from 
being chairman of the national tourism fund a government 
organization that helps finance development of tourism facilities 
he helped turn cancun off the yucatan into one of the 
caribbeans leading luxury beach resorts 
