<TEXT>
finance chiefs late friday lowered the 
value of the italian lira in the european monetary system but left 
untouched the currencies of other nations in the exchange 
arrangement 
it was the first realignment of any currency in the system in 
nearly three years 
analysts had widely predicted the finance officials would bump 
up the value of the german mark which has been gaining increasing 
strength in recent weeks against other european currencies and the 
us dollar 
the move to readjust the lira was unlikely to have any effect on 
the dollar 
in a statement the european community announced the italian 
government agreed to narrow the band in which the lira is allowed 
to fluctuate in the exchange rate mechanism of the european 
monetary system 
the arrangement seeks to prevent wide fluctuations in exchange 
rates the currencies of nine of the 12 nations of the european 
community trading bloc are linked in the exchange rate mechanism 
only the currencies of britain portugal and greece remain outside 
the italian government decided to reduce the liras range from 6 
percent to 225 percent which means the currency will be able to 
move up or down by that much from a central rate all the other 
currencies except the spanish peseta have a 225 percent band the 
peseta trades in the 6 percent range 
once the italian authorities agreed on the narrower band the 
other finance officials set the new central rate for the lira at 
15297 to the european currency unit an accounting unit created 
by the community the liras midpoint had been 148358 
the new rates will begin monday 
because the united states is not part of the european monetary 
system or ems the dollars value is not directly affected by the 
shift 
a senior european monetary official who demanded anonymity 
predicted the currency shift would be remembered as one of the 
smoothest in the history of the 10yearold monetary system 
he said telephone discussions among the finance officials began 
friday afternoon and ended nine hours later 
the finance officials also welcomed the change as a sign 
community nations were getting ready for the first phase of their 
campaign for an economic and monetary union the initial phase 
which will go into effect on july 1 calls for closer cooperation 
on economic and monetary policies 
they urged italy to work harder to pare its federal budget 
deficit this will also foster greater economic convergence in 
the community they said 
as word spread that the monetary officials were working on a 
realignment analysts expected they would rejigger the value of 
most of the currencies lowering many of them but lifting the 
german mark 
german authorities have been pressing for a realignment to 
bolster their currencys value but french officials have opposed 
any move to clip the franc 
the value of the mark has soared with the opening of borders 
between east and west germany and the economic reforms in other 
eastern european countries expectations are high that germany will 
take advantage of the openings in the east and strengthen its 
already powerful economy 
before the communitys announcement earl johnson a vice 
president at harris trust and savings bank in chicago said a 
change in only the lira would increase pressure to realign the 
other currencies 
zlatko glamuzina chief dealer at banco di sicilia in new york 
said the ems needed finetuning from time to time 
</TEXT>
