<DOCNO> AP900105-0188 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a state commission on the exxon valdez oil 
spill called friday for an overhaul of the nations 
oiltransportation system and blamed the disaster partly on the 
coast guards unduly friendly relationship with industry 
the commissions report also blames the nations worst oil spill 
on a reckless rush to profits by the oil industry and criticizes 
government agencies and the public for not insisting on stringent 
environmental safeguards 
better monitoring of tanker traffic increased use of 
doublehull tankers larger tanker crews and a stronger commitment 
by industry and government to environmental protection are among 
the reports recommendations 
obviously the present system providing minimum penalites 
for creating massive environmental damage has not deterred the 
industry from putting the coasts and oceans of the world at 
constant hazard it says 
the preliminary report by the alaska oil spill commission makes 
59 recommendations that the state and federal governments and oil 
industry can adopt to prevent oil spills and improve their spill 
response 
the report is especially critical of the coast guard for its 
confusion of mission and an unduly friendly relationship with 
industry 
the coast guard has failed the american people in providing 
oversight of the countrys oiltransportation system the report 
says enforcement must be strengthened and the penalty structure 
raised 
the report blames the coast guards lax safety enforcement and 
reduced state oversight on the national mood under president 
reagan toward less government regulation 
safety does not do well in a laissezfaire environment it 
says 
lt ray massey a coast guard spokesman in juneau said the 
agency had not received a copy of the report and would have no 
comment les rogers a spokesman for exxon co usa in houston also 
declined to comment 
the alaska legislature formed the investigatory commission in 
the weeks after the exxon valdez spill last spring in which nearly 
11 million gallons of alaska crude gushed into prince william 
sound its seven members were appointed by gov steve cowper 
this disaster could have been prevented not by tanker 
captains and crews who are only fallible human beings but by an 
advanced oiltransportation system designed to minimize human 
error commission chairman walt parker said in the reports 
foreward 
the captain of the tanker joseph hazelwood was fired amid 
charges he had been drunk at the time of the accident his trial is 
scheduled to begin jan 22 
parker was on a task force that helped set tanker standards for 
the port valdez trade in the late 1970s he said that when tankers 
began moving oil from the transalaska pipeline at valdez in 1977 
a good system to prevent spills was in place but the system fell 
apart because of legal action by the oil industry that preempted 
the state from enforcing many of its rules 
the shippers simply stopped following the rules and the coast 
guard stopped enforcing them parker said 
tankers originally were to remain inside tanker lanes at all 
times in the sound and slow down to minimum speed when ice was 
present he said the exxon valdez was allowed to go outside the 
lanes at full speed when it neared ice which led to it running 
aground on bligh reef 
the original rules were consistently violated primarily to 
ensure that tankers passing through prince william sound did not 
lose time by slowing down for ice or waiting for winds to to 
abate the report says concern for profits in the 1980s 
obliterated the concern for safe operations that existed in 1977 
the report also cites the state legislatures failure to provide 
enough money for the department of environmental conservation 
which is responsible for spill prevention and cleanup plans 
the departments small staff was overwhelmed by technical 
licensing and permitting activities leaving no opportunity for the 
agency to perform its role as overall environmental policy 
watchdog it says 
cowper described the report as a cold and sober assessment of 
what happened in the exxon valdez disaster 
a key event here was the striking down of alaskas laws that 
would have controlled tanker movements and the degree of 
preparation for oil spills cowper said at a news conference 
the commission came to the conclusion that our oilspill response 
capability is still primitive 
cowper and state house speaker sam cotten said legislation to 
adopt some of the reports recommendations may be considered during 
the 1990 legislative session which begins monday 
its a little bit too early to specifically respond to the 
spill reports findings right now but i think we will probably do 
whatever is recommended here cowper said 
cotten said he was unsure if the legislature has the will to get 
any new spill laws passed this session some legislators have said 
they first want to take a second look at the package of spill 
bills they quickly passed last spring after the exxon valdez 
spill 
among the reports other recommendations 
the party responsible for the spill not be in charge of the 
cleanup a spiller should be obligated to respond with the 
resources it can summon but government should command the 
response the report says 
a formal command system with a predesignated coordinator be 
established to handle the cleanup a lesson from the exxon valdez 
spill is that such a system is needed to avoid confusion and 
disagreements between the agencies and companies involved the 
report says 
congress either strengthen the coast guards ability to respond 
to spills or transfer its cleanup duties to the army corps of 
engineers the report says congress also needs to provide more 
money for the environmental protection agency for spill prevention 
and response 
</TEXT>
