the noncommunist government on friday 
acknowledged widespread shortages after a radical economic plan 
took effect but it urged patience to allow for the transformation 
of polands economy to capitalism 
the first few days are behind us so there is a lot of 
confusion anxiety and panic understandable in a situation of deep 
and radical changes which also are being introduced quickly said 
government spokeswoman malgorzata niezabitowska 
shoppers wiped out supplies of flour sugar and meat in many 
stores after the announcement of sharp increases for many goods and 
services monday and tuesday 
we have to give time so the medicine can work we have to show 
patience and calm so the new economic mechanisms can start 
working she said 
deputy finance minister marek dabrowski said problems in food 
deliveries led to shortages especially for meat and butter and 
that some enterprises were having trouble paying their bills 
the solidarityled government was encouraged by the 
stabilization of the zloty following a 32 percent devaluation on 
monday an increase in bank deposits and an improvement in export 
figures in december dabrowski said 
one of the central elements of the plan which aims to halt 
polands 900 percent annual inflation and transform an economy 
directly managed by communists for four decades is to make the 
zloty a convertible currency 
poland until now has had two rates of exchange an official 
rate set by the government and a higher black market rate 
this week for the first time in memory the average official 
rate of 9500 zlotys to the dollar was higher than the unofficial 
rate 
the government hopes that a convertible currency will help 
attract foreign investors who until now have hesitated to develop 
projects in poland without a guarantee of being able to expatriate 
their profits 
but dabrowski said individual consumers have suffered partially 
because producers have withheld reverves of meat from the market 
