people with aids should be called just that not aids victims 
the gay and lesbian alliance against defamation says in its style 
guidelines victim the activists say is better used to 
describe the target of a criminal act 
similarly children born with aids should not be called 
innocent victims of the disease as that implies other people 
with aids are guilty of something the alliance says 
in its language guidelines special olympics asks that people 
with handicaps not be labeled by their disabilities a person 
uses a wheelchair rather than is confined or restricted to a 
wheelchair the guidelines say a person has a seizure disorder 
or epilepsy rather than is epileptic 
pat krebs director of education for outreach projects for 
special olympics acknowledged that some of the guidelines border 
on euphemism physically challenged she said may not be an 
appropriate substitute for physically disabled the latter 
replacing crippled 
all the same even accepted shorthand quickly can become 
outdated and offensive at the turn of the century the labels used 
for degrees of retardation were idiot imbecile and moron krebs 
said 
then those terms took on such negative connotations with 
society krebs said so were constantly changing terminology 
other snappy labels star wars or prodemocracy may 
add little to our understanding of complicated issues 
the genesis for this is really television with its short 
attention span and its desire to compress everything into little 
nuggets of information said media critic mark hertsgaard author 
of on bended knee the press and the reagan presidency 
i think the use of shorthand has becomes at least as much a 
liability as an asset hertsgaard said it discourages any kind 
of nuance or complex understanding of political events 
prodemocracy hertsgaard and others say doesnt spell out 
differences between movements in china east germany 
czechoslovakia poland and the soviet union 
but time is so short for elaboration 
said abcs greenfield if im doing a piece for the network 
