<DOCNO> AP900105-0221 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal regulators have taken the first 
tentative step in what may be a long journey toward barring brokers 
from trading for themselves as well as their customers 
the practice is known as dual trading and while legal it has 
been controversial in the wake of fraud scandals at the nations 
two largest futures exchanges 
officials of those exchanges the chicago board of trade and the 
chicago mercantile exchange immediately criticized the move 
thursday by the commodity futures trading commission 
the federal agency voted to consider placing some restrictions 
on dual trading on some contracts at the seven largest futures 
exchanges 
the fivemember cftc which oversees the futures industry voted 
unanimously to submit for public comment a proposed rule that would 
phase in some limits on dual trading over a 12month period 
critics claim dual trading creates the potential for conflicts 
of interest and possible fraud 
supporters however say dual trading helps keep markets liquid 
and thus less volatile when there are few customer orders 
not all futures exchanges would be affected by the proposed 
rules change which may not win final approval for as much as a 
year 
upon approval the initial dual trading restrictions will be 
reviewed and the cftc will consider extending or easing those 
limits said chairwoman wendy gramm 
we do intend to proceed carefully and thoughtfully in that 
process she said 
the cftc also voted unanimously to accept a staff recommendation 
that the agency keep closer tabs on broker associations to 
prevent possible trading abuses such as those undercovered in 
chicago last year 
in november the cftc released a study disputing the economic 
benefits of dual trading 
but commissioner robert davis who reluctantly agreed to submit 
the proposal for public comment as a way of obtaining more data 
expressed reservations about making a decision based on a single 
study 
before tampering with the formula other hypotheses must be 
tested other data must be analyzed and alternative explanations of 
the results must be considered he said 
legislation that would severely limit dual trading is pending in 
both the house and senate 
the proposal would bar floor brokers from trading or placing 
futures or options orders for their own accounts while handling a 
customers order on the same day in the same commodity 
the chicago board of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange 
which account for about 90 percent of the nations futures trading 
volume would each be required to impose dual trading restrictions 
on just one of their three most actively traded agricultural 
commodities and their singlemost active financial commodityn 
five other exchanges the new york mercantile exchange the 
commodity exchange inc the coffee sugar amp cocoa exchange inc 
the midamerica commodity exchange and the new york cotton exchange 
would have to impose restrictions on only one of their two most 
active commodities 
and four smaller exchanges the kansas city board of trade 
minneapolis grain exchange new york futures exchange and the 
chicago rice and cotton exchange would be exempt from 
restrictions during the implementation period 
cbot president and chief executive thomas r donovan said 
there are futures exchanges developing all around the world and 
most allow dual trading if we cannot handle customer business 
because of illfounded restrictions on trading then we will lose 
that business to our foreign competitors 
added cbot chairman karsten mahlmann the cftcs proposal to 
ban dual trading flies in the face of the evidence of its own 
study which shows benefits from dual trading and which provides no 
evidence that dual trading imposes costs or harms customers 
on broker associations the cftc staff recommended adopting a 
rule defining the term and requiring exchanges to register the 
members of such associations 
the commissions division of trading and markets said 
registration of broker association members would allow exchanges to 
monitor their trading activity as a safeguard against abuses 
broker associations are formal or informal groups of futures 
traders formed to provide more capital to finance trades and more 
people to handle them 
supporters of broker associations claim they help service 
customer orders by increasing the capital of individual brokers and 
providing continuous service 
but the cftc staff found that broker associations may increase 
the potential for certain types of trading abuses 
the cftc study was an outgrowth of last years undercover 
investigation of trading at the two chicago exchanges that resulted 
in scores of indictments 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

