<DOCNO> AP900105-0223 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency has 
proposed regulations to reduce hydrocarbon releases from cars and 
trucks when gasoline evaporates 
proposed changes in how vehicle emission tests are to be run 
would require automakers to modify vehicle emission control 
equipment in a way that atmospheric hydrocarbon levles would fall 
about 5 percent the agency said thursday 
the modifications are said to be minor and should add only about 
10 to the cost of a car an amount that would be more than offset 
by better fuel economy according to the epa 
hydrocarbons or volatile organic compounds released from motor 
vehicles react with the sun to form ozone when also combined with 
particulates in the air the result is the smog that plagues many 
of the nations urban centers 
the regulatory proposal announced thursday applies only to 
hydrocarbon releases from the normal evaporation of gasoline 
especiallyin hot weather both when a vehicle is running and when 
it is idle 
the proposal would require emissions testing procedures to be 
changed to assure that such evaporated fuel losses are better 
controlled especially during summer driving and after a vehicle 
has been idle for a day or more 
in some cases automakers are expected to equip vehicles with 
larger charcoal cannisters so emission control systems are not 
overloaded by gasoline vapors or make other changes to improve the 
systems ability to purge such vapors when a car is running 
officials said 
the new requirements when made final later this year will 
apply to all gasolinefueled passenger cars and trucks 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

