the bush administration considered but 
rejected the idea of proposing new taxes on various materials in an 
effort to encourage recycling an administration official said 
the official who spoke thursday on condition that he not be 
named said the proposal had been given a good chance of becoming 
part of the presidents fiscal 1991 budget request to congress but 
that it was finally rejected by the office of management and budget 
omb director richard darman stripped the proposed tax along 
with other socalled user fees to avoid charges from 
congressional democrats that presidentbush was violating his 
nonewtaxes pledge the official said 
the proposal would have imposed new taxes on paper glass 
plastic and metals that were not recycled the environmental 
protection agency which favored the tax concept as a way of 
encouraging greater use of recycled materials by us industry 
wants to reduce the nations output of waste by 25 percentby 1992 
bush as part of his 1988 presidential campaign promised to 
make a national commitment to reduce waste by recycling and 
developing technology that produces less waste 
by making productsmade from virgin materials more expensive 
supporters of the tax had argued it would encourage businesses to 
use more recycled materials 
