<TEXT>
attorneys for admitted inside trader robert 
freeman are seeking to block the government from making public a 
sentencing recommendation that alleges a series of new and unproven 
fraudulent transactions 
the government also names several individualsin the memo who 
allegedly lied during the 2year grand jury investigation of the 
freeman case according to documents filed in manhattan federal 
court 
the dispute hinges on the disclosure of sensitive grand jury 
matters and has delayed sentencing of the former head of arbitrage 
at goldman sachs amp co arrested in 1987 in a highly publicized 
case that later fell flat 
the government contends that releasing the memo showsa broad 
range of questionable conduct by freeman that should be considered 
in sentencing freeman has admitted to one instance of insider 
trading 
in connection with his sentencing freeman loudly contends 
that this was the only occasion in which he engaged in insider 
trading assistant us attorney john mcenany wrote the 
government has evidence to the contrary which it believes the court 
should consider 
the issue marks another twist in a case that began with the 
touted february 1987 arrests of freeman and two others based on 
information linked to jailed inside trader ivan boesky 
government prosecutors boasted that initial charges were the 
tip of the iceberg but the indictments later were dropped and 
prosecutors last year abandoned an investigation of the two other 
wall street traders timothy tabor and richard wigton wigton even 
was handcuffed after his arrest 
the case now is widely viewed as the governments biggest 
embarrassment in the threeyear insider trading investigation begun 
by former us attorney rudolph giuliani 
in a draft of the sentencing memo given to defense lawyers 
prosecutors allege a series of insider trading transactions beyond 
the one freeman admitted attorneys paul curran and robert b fiske 
state in court documents 
the sentencing report has not been filed pending a ruling by 
us district judge pierre leval on whether it should be kept under 
seal or allowed into the public record 
the governments allegations are false and they unfairly 
implicate not only mr freeman but also other persons none of whom 
has been charged with respect to these allegations curran and 
fiske state in a motion seeking to seal the memo 
the government and the wall street journal have filed papers 
arguing that the sentencing document should be released 
freeman pleaded guilty last august to one count of mail fraud 
for using inside information in january 1986 to trade in connection 
with the proposed takeover of beatrice cos by the investment firm 
kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
he admitted receiving the information from former kidder 
peabody amp co investment banker martin a siegel who has pleaded 
guilty to two counts and is awaiting sentencing 
freemans lawyers contend thatonly material dealing with the 
beatrice transaction should be made public 
freeman is someone who cares about his reputation if he is 
seen as someone who has been trading with the abandon of an ivan 
boesky hell be unemployable said john c coffee jr a 
columbia university securities law professor 
in court papers filed last month attorneys for freeman charge 
that the sentencing report will tarnish mrn freemans already 
scarred reputation and cause serious injury to the reputation of 
others 
some individuals are branded as liars still others are 
accused of insider trading the lawyers state the stigma that 
the publication of such accusations would impose is irrevocable 
 
the sentencing memo reportedly cites about a dozen instances of 
uncharged insider trading by freeman including two named in his 
original indictment and includes the names of some who testified 
before the grand jury 
under existing case law grand jury secrecy protects defendants 
from disclosure of accusations that are not contained in an 
indictment returned by the panel which determines whether or what 
criminal charges can be filed 
in the freeman case the government acknowledges that a 
significant portion of the memo relies on grand jury matters 
but that no testimony is directly quoted and the information is 
merely summarized 
mcenany stated the government agreed only not to prosecute 
freeman for other matters uncovered in its investigation the 
supreme court has allowed sentencing judges to consider alleged 
conduct that a defendant has not been convicted of or admitted to 
freeman faces a maximum five years in prison and up to 19 
million in fines 
