<DOCNO> AP900105-0235 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
stockmarket investors have wasted no time 
lately speculating on the potential benefits of growing 
international trade in an increasingly democratic world 
in recent weeks they have scrambled to buy shares of country 
funds investing in corners of the globe ranging from germany to 
chile to thailand 
as wall street closed the books on 1989 these funds clearly 
stamped themselves as the latest in a long line of hot financial 
properties that helped keep the bull market bubbling throughout the 
80s 
among the 42 issues listed on the new york stock exchange that 
doubled or more in price during 1989 no less than eight were 
closedend investment companies specializing in securities of a 
single country or region of the world 
spain fund which almost tripled asia pacific fund thai fund 
and the germany fund all made the top ten 
world events provided several sparks to keep enthusiasm for 
these stocks going the most obvious was the toppling of economic 
and political barriers in eastern europe after decades in the 
shadow of communism 
the apparent end to the cold war raised visions of vast new 
opportunities for the economies of western europe which had 
already begun to gear up for business and financial alliances set 
to take effect in 1992 
heiko thieme investment strategist for deutsche bank capital 
corp in new york projects that the opening up of eastern europe 
will in time raise the worlds total economic output by a full 
percentage point 
meanwhile investors searched frenetically elsewhere in the 
world for upwardly mobile nations that might be ready to follow in 
the footsteps of such modern success stories as japan 
even if that reasoning were as good as it sounded however many 
analysts who have watched the mania develop say buyers of country 
funds seem to be willing to pay almost any price to satisfy their 
appetites 
nearly all the country funds are closedend investment 
companies they operate in much the same manner as mutual funds 
except that their sponsors do not continuously buy and sell shares 
at the prevailing net asset value 
instead the funds have a fixed number of shares that trade on 
stock exchanges or in the overthecounter market just like other 
common stocks so the price they command is determined by market 
forces and can fluctuate above at a premium to or below at 
a discount to the net asset value 
some country funds notably in the far east have traded at 
premiums almost all of the time since their inception in part 
because foreigners have few or no other ways to participate in 
those countries markets 
lately however other country funds in europe and elsewhere 
that once traded at discounts also have soared past the pershare 
value of the investments they own 
in recent months the share prices of single country closedend 
funds have been bid up to unrealistic prices asserts norman 
tepper an analyst at the value line investment survey in the 
advisory services latest appraisal of the group 
however bright the funds longterm prospects most major 
world economies are either experiencing inflation rising interest 
rates or stagflation tepper says most will probably show 
slower economic growth in 1990 several stock markets look rather 
perilous 
as has been demonstrated in the past a popular closedend fund 
can keep trading at lofty premiums for a long time but analysts 
point out that a big premium in a fund is like a high 
priceearnings ratio for an industrial stock suggesting that 
expectations of many good things are already built into the price 
securities in that position are considered vulnerable to any 
disappointment that might arise from say greater weakness than 
expected in the pace of the world economy 
in teppers view the present circumstances certainly suggest 
that investors exercise caution with respect to foreign 
investments and in particular closedend funds with stakes in 
overseasbased companies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

