<DOCNO> AP900105-0237 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
shortterm interest rates should drop in the 
coming months as the federal reserve board eases monetary policy 
further to forestall a recession most economists believe 
declining interest rates are good news to bondholders since it 
means the value or price of their fixedreturn investments should 
increase 
the fed has been easing interest rates since the middle of last 
year when it became apparent that the economy was slowing the 
policy is consistent with the feds aim of a soft landing for 
the economy which is in the eighth year of a recordbreaking 
expansion 
david m blitzer chief economist at standard amp poors corp is 
among the more pessimistic observers of the health of the economy 
the us is teetering on the edge of recession he wrote 
last week in a commentary 
he said that unless the fed eases rates further the economy 
will fall over that cliff 
interest rates for 1990 are relatively easy to forecast 
blitzer said either the fed will ease and rates will come down 
now or it will not ease there will be a recession and rates will 
come down later 
barclays de zoete wedd government securities inc predicts the 
government will report in late january a 1 percent decline in 
fourthquarter real gross national product that decline the 
investment house projects will prompt the fed to lower its 
discount rate for the first time since the central bank has been 
headed by alan greenspan who took charge in the summer of 1987 
the discount rate currently 7 percent is the interest the fed 
charges member banks for loans and it provides a floor for other 
interest rates such as bank loan rates 
previously the fed has worked to lower general interest rates 
by easing the federal funds rate the rate banks charge on 
overnight loans to each other however the financial consulting 
firm griggs amp santow inc cautions that while the gnp figure is an 
important gauge of the economy the fourthquarter figure may be 
distorted by the hurricanes the california earthquake and strikes 
during the three months 
moreover a quite weak gnp number can occur even as important 
areas of the economy are doing well the firm says thus even 
though gnp will be weak in the fourth quarter the consumer 
energy export investment and nondefense spending sectors are all 
likely to expand 
other experts are less certain of continued fed easing as long 
as core inflation remains at about 45 percent recent weather and 
accidentrelated increases in the prices of crude oil orange juice 
and other commodities fuel this belief in addition some 
economists say not all signs point to a recession 
barring either a severe financial disruption or the imminence 
of recession we foresee no quick exit from a stilltight monetary 
policy john lonski senior economist for moodys investors 
service inc wrote recently without pressing reasons to do 
otherwise the danger of higher inflation may have to pass before 
the fed relaxes its firm monetary grip 
many analysts say the predicted drop in interest rates will 
occur almost entirely among shortterm bonds yields on longterm 
issues such as the treasurys benchmark 30year bond should 
remain steady 
currently the 30year bond is trading at about 8percent the 
belief is that the yield will not decline due to the need to 
attract overseas investors in the bonds which help finance the 
federal deficit interest rates in west germany and japan have been 
rising increasing the competition for global investors funds 
in addition the rate may remain at its current level due to the 
45 percent core inflation which cuts the actual yield by more 
than half analysts say this factor may limit any drop in 
shortterm yields as well as bond investors continue to demand 
compensation for inflation 
with short term rates dropping more than longterm issues the 
treasury yield curve which plots the yield of treasury securities 
along a line measuring their maturity will steepen further in a 
positive direction this means investors will be rewarded ever more 
for tying up their money in longerterm bonds 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

