<TEXT>
phoenix millionaire charles h keating jr 
the central figure in a 2 billion savings and loan scandal 
acknowledged today that bookkeeping by his thrift institution hid 
the true buyer in a major real estate deal 
but keating chairman of american continental corp parent 
company of lincoln savings and loan association of irvine calif 
said the bookkeeping was a proper part of a land syndication deal 
and that government examiners should not have cared about the 
identity of the true buyer 
us district judge stanley sporkin who is hearing evidence in 
keatings suit to overturn the government seizure of lincoln last 
april reacted skeptically asking how is it you can manage 
billiondollar businesses and have transactions where the paperwork 
did not reflect what took place 
when you run a bank or a savings and loan you have the 
highest responsibility of anyone because youre not dealing just 
with stockholders youre dealing with peoples savings sporkin 
told keating the only way regulators can ensure that an 
institution is being run properly is if the books and records 
accurately reflect transactions 
in 1987 lincoln sold 1000 acres for which it had paid 3 
million to westcontinental mortgage co for 14 million however 
government regulators maintain that westcontinental was just a 
straw buyer for arizona developer and stockbroker ernest c garcia 
they say the land transaction was improperly linked with another 
transaction between lincoln and garcia on the same day 
keating told the judge i cant believe that anyone was 
innocent of the fact that the deal was being made with garcia 
everybody who was there and present at that time including the 
government examiners knew what we were doing 
however in response to a later question from his own attorney 
keating acknowledged that he did not know whether his own auditors 
knew that garcia was the buyer 
and kevin oconnell a supervisory official with the federal 
office of thrift supervision told reporters after keatings 
testimony there is nothing in the record that we were ever 
advised that garcia was the real buyer 
on thursday keating broke his selfimposed silence with more 
than an hour of testimony in which he described how he used lincoln 
to finance massive residential projects in the phoenix area 
keating has had little to say in public since september when 
government regulators filed a 11 billion fraud and racketeering 
civil suit charging he operated lincoln for his own and his 
familys benefit a grand jury in los angeles is examining possible 
criminal charges against keating 
the government seized lincoln in april claiming it was 
operating in an unsafe and unsound manner 
in november keating asserted his constitutional protection 
against selfincrimination and refused to testify before a house 
committee investigating the failure 
but keating sought the court action and in response to the 
judges questions he readily described his disappointment when the 
seizure of lincoln blocked the completion of a large residential 
project west of phoenix 
the saddest thing in my life is that we were brought to this 
pass he said 
keating also is at the center of a senate ethics committee 
investigation examining the actions of five senators who accepted 
more than 13 million in contributions from the financier and 
later met on his behalf with federal regulators 
in thursdays hearing government investigators focused on a 
stock transaction with garcia which denied up to 12 million in 
profits to a lincoln subsidiary and instead benefited american 
continental which provided keating and his family with millions of 
dollars in salaries and benefits 
the lincoln subsidiary sold 1 million of memorex common stock 
to garcia the subsidiary retained an option to repurchase the 
shares for 425 million should their value skyrocket 
four months later in late october 1987 american continental 
repurchased the stock from garcia for 2 million and the 
subsidiary headed by keatings son charles h keating iii waived 
its option 
later in march and april 1988 american continental sold the 
stock for 133 million because it waived its option the lincoln 
subsidiary didnt get any of the profits which would have offset 
taxpayer losses in the sampls later failure 
the memorex transaction is one of four deals the government has 
cited as examples of unsafe and unsound practices that 
justified its takeover of lincoln 
the elder keating testified he approved the decision for 
american continental to buy back the memorex stock from garcia 
but he said i dont believe that i made the decision where to 
put it i dont know who made the decision on waiving the 
lincolns buyback option 
he said he assumed that was done because federal sampl regulators 
were pressing lincoln to get out of stock market investments 
however sporkin said i cant see the regulators objecting 
to retaining the memorex option which could only benefit lincoln 
