a federal grand jury has added three 
charges against a former usx corp official in an investigation of 
pensions the company awarded to union negotiators in 1983 
james bruce johnston indicted on one felony count last month 
now faces four charges and may stand trial with usx and two 
birmingham union leaders in march 
johnston said in a statement that the new indictment returned 
thursday and made public today is outrageous 
the charges against johnston usx and thermon phillips and eb 
rich of the united steelworkers of america stem from a federal 
investigation of the negotiations leading to a 1983 union contract 
for usxs fairfield works at birmingham 
the indictments alleged that as part of the negotiations the 
company agreed to secretly set up pensions for rich phillips and 
four other union negotiators although the six were not eligible 
for the benefits in return the grand jury alleged rich and 
phillips agreed to make concessions in the fairfield works contract 
johnston then a usx laborrelations executive played a key 
role in usxs change of its pensionplan rules to include the union 
negotiators 
thursdays indictment charged johnston of mcmurray pa with 
conspiracy causing usx to make the pension payments to phillips 
and rich and causing the companys pension fund to fail to inform 
its participants of the rule change the grand jury had indicted 
johnston on the latter charge two weeks ago 
in a court document assistant us attorney michael rasmussen 
reported the government would seek to combine johnstons case with 
that of the company and union leaders who face trial march 5 
johnston if convicted on all four counts could face a maximum 
penalty of 20 years in prison and a 11 million fine said us 
attorney frank w donaldson 
johnston repeated a statement he issued last month in which he 
defended his actions and those of the company in granting the 
pensions he said the union had requested the rule change for 
years other large companies had similar rules and the change was 
based in part on a written legal opinion of the us department of 
labor 
the company rescinded the change in 1987 after learning of 
recent court decisions indicating it was illegal johnston said 
fairfield employees had sued the company and the union leaders 
claiming collusion in the granting of the pensions and seeking the 
voiding of the 1983 agreement which cut wages and benefits in 
return for the reopening of the plant that lawsuit is on hold in 
birmingham federal court pending the resolution of the criminal 
charges 
