a cleanair bill pending in the senate would 
force virtually every coke plant in the nation to close 
endangering the domestic steel industry a usx corp official said 
if this legislation goes through the way it is now being 
shaped in the senate theres a good chance it will signal the end 
of cokeoven operations in the nation said philip x 
masciantonio vice president of environmental affairs for the uss 
division of usx 
if we cant make coke here we dont have a steel industry 
he told the pittsburgh press on thursday coke is a primary 
ingredient for making steel 
the toxic pollution provisions of senate bill 1630 passed last 
month by the environmental and public works committee would submit 
coke plants to strict new emissions standards and overhaul the 
clean air act in the areas of acid rain and urban smog 
environmentalists give varyng assessments of the bill 
anthony picadio a lawyer for the group against smog and 
pollution a pittsburgh environmental group that has sparred with 
usx for 20 years said he opposes the bill because coke plants 
could not meet its stringent healthprotection standard he said 
the bill would never be enforced 
but lawyers with the natural resources defense council a 
washingtonbased environmental group said the bill provides 
exemptions if pollutioncontrol technology cannot achieve the 
standards as a result theres no reason to worry that wholesale 
plant closings would occur they said 
i think its part of a general campaign by us industry to 
paint this legislation as extreme said richard ayres a senior 
attorney with the defense council 
senate majority leader george j mitchell dmaine has said the 
bill will be the first one considered when senators return jan 23 
from their winter recess 
about 40 plants in the united states bake coal in ovens to 
produce coke usxs clairton works a sprawling network of ovens 
and smokestacks along the monongahela river at clairton is the 
largest coke plant in the nation 
the senate bill would require each coke plant to gradually 
reduce air emissions to the point that emissions would pose no more 
than a one in 1 million risk of cancer to a person living downwind 
all his life masciantonio said 
an environmental protection agency analysis shows that coke 
plants pose among the highest cancer risks of all us industrial 
plants for example oven emissions from the clairton plant pose a 
cancer risk of one in 130 in the most extreme hypothetical case 
masciantonio said 
a 10000fold reduction in emissions would be needed to achieve 
the bills goal and thats not possible with todays technology 
he said 
</TEXT>
