the agriculture department announced on friday 
the rates for advance federal payments when farmers begin to sign 
up for 1990 crop programs later in the month 
keith bjerke executive vice president of the departments 
commodity credit corp said the advance payments will be reduced 
by 14 percent as required by the omnibus budget reconciliation act 
of 1989 
farmers will be able to sign up in 1990 crop programs jan 16 
through april 13 at local offices of the departments agricultural 
stabilization and conservation service 
the cash advances are made to help tide farmers over until crops 
are harvested and will be deducted from their total deficiency 
payments at the end of the season 
deficiency payments based on a crops acreage and program 
yield per acre make up the difference between a target price and 
the average market price during a specified period of the marketing 
season 
adjusted advance deficiency payment rates for 1990 allowing for 
the 14 percent budget reductions include 
wheat 3367 cents per bushel 
corn 3367 cents per bushel 
sorghum 3419 cents per bushel 
barley 84 cents per bushel 
oats none 
upland cotton 3685 cents per pound 
extralong staple cotton none 
rice 15725 per 100 pounds 
